review_blob: snifter.  Pours a nice peachy orange (from the hibiscus?), effervescent and clear with an off white, pink-tinged head.  Smells sour, apples, pineapple, belgian yeast, still smells like a tripel at its core, biscuity.  Taste: sour apples, belgian yeast, biscuity and caramel, finishes slightly dry with a hint of smoke, a super faint woodsy, tobacco-ish flavor on the back of the tongue.  Crisp palate, not too sticky.  Overall pretty awesome.  Im not too familiar with feijoa but im lookin up where to get some now!
beer_name: New Belgium Lips of Faith - Heavenly Feijoa Tripel

review_blob: Pours a rocky eggshell colored head that reduces to a thin film after a few minutes.  Smells faintly grassy, with even a bit of honey character.  Front/middle of tongue, tastes sweet, with a slight spice, back the hop presence is definitely there, but for being a 70 IBU beer, this doesnt taste it.  Finishes pleasantly bitter, and sweet.  Super balanced, with a perfect hop presence.  Will buy more.
beer_name: New Belgium Hop Kitchen  #1 - Hoppy Bock Lager

review_blob: Poured a big frothy eggshell white head, pale straw yellow hue body.  Smells malty, mild spice from the hops, noble?  Tastes so smooth, finishes sweet, but perfectly balanced with hop bitterness (no significant hop flavors, but hop presence obviously helps).  Palate is medium bodied.  SUPER drinkable, definitely a session beer, but also thought provoking.  New Glarus is making me reconsider a good lager for my go-to summer drink.

Pours a fluffy, consistent cream colored head.  Color is a clear, ruby dark brown.  Foam recedes after a couple of minutes.  Smells faintly of coffee and roasted malt, Tastes much more robust than I was expecting after the lighter-than-expected color.  Smooth, up front coffee and chocolate, slight vanilla, roasty, slightly smoky; boozy but expectedly so.  Taste stays on the back of my tongue for several minutes.  NOM

Had this for the first time at Roast Public House in Madison, Wisconsin on state street, but have been a frequent customer since my awakening.  Pours a dark, oil black with an espresso colored head.  Head fades as you drink, but in a tulip or snifter, theres some nice bubbling and residual, light carbonation after the first few sips.  Smells heavily of chocolate and coffee, even some toffee.  Taste: chocolate! coffee! toffee! chocolate! oaty/chewy! smooth and silky.  Bitter, but in a way that balances the otherwise sweetness from the grain bill and chocolate.  This is my favorite stout.  Mocha on the palate even 10 minutes after tasting(/finishing).  Damn, Im gonna go have another.

Was expecting a bit more body than I got.  Had it on nitro after the brewery tour.  Poured a nice black, with a caramel and eggshell head.  Smelled like coffee and chocolate.  Light and roasty in its taste.  Light body, but smooth (attribute that to the nitro).  Pretty average, but still good.
woohoo, rating no. 10!  Bready, malty, perhaps biscuity.  Caramel notes, good beer for converting friends not accustomed to craft beer.  Gotta start somewhere!
If I had had to choose between hoppy wheat or wheat, id choose the hoppy wheat.  The hoppiness comes through in the aroma more than the taste.  I dig

Beer staple from my hometown,  gotta love wheat.  Solid wheat beer for a solid brewery.  Poured moderate, two finger head, a turbid, straw yellow body with a white head.  Aroma of malt/wheat, minimal hop presence. Tastes like a wheat, some citrus and a nice bitter finish.  Nice and grainy mouthfeel, chewy like lots of wheats.  Boulevard is one of the reasons Im so proud to be from KC.

Pours a nice blackish brown, slight red hues.  Smells piney! Taste slightly of coffee, yet spicy from the rye, yet bitter from the hops.  Really confusing thanks to that midnight wheat, but really, really good.  Luckily I gots three mo!
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - Grainstorm Black Rye IPA

review_blob: Pours suuuuper heady, a nice dark, brownish wish a subtle hint of red.  Big head.  Smells of malt and molasses, tastes nice and funky, but almost crisp.  Definite yeast characteristics, strong maltiness and some more carmelly/molassesy notes in there.  Dangerously drinkable too.  I didnt feel at all exhausted by the 8.9%.  A bit of a slick mouthfeel, but it works with the beer.  Some slight lacing.  Me like.

Damn.  Pours a nice heady orangey hue, pretty effervescent.  Smells ber malty, with lots of apply/pear and maybe even some tropical fruits thrown in there, with a hint of spice,.  Tastes exactly how Id hoped.  Palate isnt too sticky, but dextriny enough that the bitterness left on the back of the tongue makes me want more.  Of course, not dry like an IPA but dry enough to fool my mouth into thinking it needs more quenching...which I dont much mind!

Poured into a Lakefront Brewery pint glass.  Pours with a one-finger head, not much lacing.  Straw yellow, slightly hazy.  Smells of grainy and orangey.  Tastes like a wheat beer with the typical orange but some perceivable metallic taste. Finishes dry.  Not bad.  Not excellent.

Poured into a standard pint glass.  Nice 2 finger head, reduces to a ring of carbonation and some residual dextrin on the surface.  Some residual lacing left after the head disappeared.  Once in the glass, crystal clear, and light.  Smells strongly of malt and honey, and some slight grassy hoppy notes.  Tastes strongly of malt, with a perfect bit of honey.  Sweet.  I dont know very much about heller bock, but the dextriny mouthfeel was a pleasant surprise (based purely on the visual).  Solid.

Cracked this one open in time for valentines day.  Poured thick, black, and syrupy.  Nice mocha colored head.  Aromas of chocolate, chocolate and more chocolate.  Looks and smells awesome.  More than anything I taste oak, vanilla, and bourbon.  Limited chocolate flavor and a hint of coffee.    Palate is slick.  I have to say, the bourbon was a bit much for me.  Still, obviously a well crafted stout.  Maybe there was still bourbon left in the barrel when they filled it... ha

Pours a crystal clear straw/orange color, fluffy head reduces to some nice lacing and a ring of carbonation.  Aroma of barnyard funk, sweet hops, orange and perhaps pineapple.  Tastes like a hopped up tripel, yeasty yet a strong malt backbone with an addition of some citrus and maybe some beet candi sugar, finishes dry, but not before a bit of a hoppy kick has anything to say about it.  Ill buy again.
